import std.algorithm;
import std.array;

// Function to perform Timsort
function timsort(arr: array<int>) : array<int> =
    let n = arr.length;
    let i = 0;
    let j = n - 1;
    while i < j:
        while i < j and arr[i] <= 0:
            i += 1;
        while i < j and arr[j] >= 0:
            j -= 1;
        if i < j:
            arr[i], arr[j] = arr[j], arr[i];
        else:
            break;
    return arr;
```

This function works by iteratively moving the insertion point (`i`) and the end point (`j`) of the array towards each other until they meet in the middle. At each step, it swaps the elements at the current positions (`arr[i]` and `arr[j]`) if they are in the wrong order. This process continues until the array is sorted.

The time complexity of the Timsort algorithm is O(n log n), which is the best possible time complexity for sorting algorithms. However, the space complexity is O(n), which is the worst possible space complexity for sorting algorithms. This is because the algorithm requires an auxiliary array to store the sorted elements.

